{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538178","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538178"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16155"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16155"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.3,0.17,0.03,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8846"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8846","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8846"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16155"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49597"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4699"},{"type":"tags","id":"4701"},{"type":"tags","id":"4724"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21087"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35108"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to a sexual health clinic anxiously requesting HIV post-exposure prophylaxis. Thirty-six hours ago, he had receptive oral intercourse with a casual male partner. Today, he learned that his partner is HIV-positive but taking antiretroviral medication. He reports that there was no injury to himself or his partner. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are no signs of oral mucosal injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Advise that he does not require PEP","Commence tenofovir/emtricitabine and dolutegravir","Immediate HIV testing with PEP if positive","Urgent infectious diseases consultation","Commence tenofovir/emtricitabine alone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a common clinical scenario where post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is requested but not indicated. The risk of HIV transmission from receptive oral sex is extremely low, even with a known HIV-positive source. It is unknown if his partner has an undetectable viral load; however, this information would not change management in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdvising that he does not require PEP\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management. The patient should be counselled about the extremely low risk of transmission (estimated at less than 0.04% per act for receptive oral sex) and offered baseline and follow-up HIV testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases where the partner\u0027s viral load is unknown or detectable, and there has been significant oral mucosal injury, PEP should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenofovir/emtricitabine and dolutegravir\u003C/strong\u003E is the recommended PEP regimen when indicated, but PEP is not recommended for oral sex exposures due to the negligible risk of transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETenofovir/emtricitabine alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate if PEP were indicated, as guidelines recommend three-drug regimens when PEP is needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUrgent infectious diseases consultation\u003C/strong\u003E is not necessary given the clear guidelines about oral exposure and the very low risk of transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArranging \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmediate HIV testing with PEP if positive\u003C/strong\u003E represents a misunderstanding of PEP principles. A positive HIV test would indicate pre-existing infection, not infection from the recent exposure, and PEP would not be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["HIV post-exposure prophylaxis (PEP) is not routinely recommended for receptive oral sex even with a known HIV-positive source.","The risk of HIV transmission from receptive oral sex is extremely low, estimated at less than 0.04% if no mucosal injury is present."],"references":["Wood LF, Chahroudi A, Chen HL, Jaspan HB, Sodora DL. The oral mucosa immune environment and oral transmission of HIV/SIV. Immunological Reviews. 2013 Jun 16;254(1):34\u201353. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC3821196/","PEP Guidelines: Quick-Reference [Internet]. ASHM PEP Guidelines. 2024. Available at: https://pep.guidelines.org.au/pep-guidelines-quick-reference/","Baggaley RF, White RG, Boily MC . Systematic review of orogenital HIV-1 transmission probabilities. International Journal of Epidemiology. 2008 Jul 29;37(6):1255\u201365. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/ije/article/37/6/1255/731568"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49597"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16155"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49597"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T03:35:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T03:37:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8846"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{